%I A395187 #4 Apr 21 2026 00:14:58
%S A395187 1,1,1,4,43,1851,325673,156480861
%N A395187 Number of unlabeled minimally 5-rigid graphs on n vertices.
%C A395187 A graph G is d-rigid, if every generic realization p in dimension d yields a framework (G,p) that is infinitesimally d-rigid; i.e., all its infinitesimal flexes are trivial. It is minimally d-rigid if it is d-rigid but looses this property upon deletion of any edge.
%C A395187 Every minimally 5-rigid graph with n>5 is (5,15)-sparse, that is every subgraph with n'>=5 vertices spans at most 5n'-15 edges. Minimally 5-rigid graphs have 5n-15 edges and hence are (5,15)-tight but not every (5,15)-tight graph is minimally 5-rigid.
%H A395187 Matteo Gallet, Georg Grasegger, Matthias Himmelmann and Jan Legerský, <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2505.22652">PyRigi -- a general-purpose Python package for the rigidity and flexibility of bar-and-joint frameworks</a>, arXiv:2505.22652 [math.MG], 2025.
%H A395187 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18548603">Dataset of minimally d-rigid graphs</a>, 2026.
%H A395187 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7457820">RigiComp - A Mathematica package for computational rigidity of graphs</a>, 2022.
%H A395187 PyRigi Developers, <a href="https://pyrigi.github.io/PyRigi/math/rigidity.html">Rigidity Theory</a>, 2025.
%H A395187 Walter Whiteley, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/conm/197">Some matroids from discrete applied geometry</a>, 1996.
%e A395187 The complete graphs on five and six vertices are minimally 5-rigid. So is the complete graph on seven vertices with one edge removed.
%e A395187 The three graphs that can be obtained from the previous one by adding a new vertex and connecting it to 5 of the existing vertices, are also minimally 5-rigid.
%Y A395187 Cf. A227117, A328419, A394820.
